  "body": " Events and Sample Space   Probability is a measure of how likely the events are going to happen. Probability can range from 0 to 1, where 0 means the event to be an impossible one and 1 indicates a certain event. The probability of all the events in a sample space adds up to 1.  For example, a fair coin is tossed, we can get either a Head OR a Tail. So, only two possible outcomes are possible . But when two coins are tossed then there will be four possible outcomes, i.e .  In this chapter we are going to discuss probability in the following steps.   General terminology, definition, Probability using permutation and combination;    Probability using set theory, addition and multiplication theorem;    Independent events, conditional probability, total probability theorem, Baye's theorem;    Probability distribution, random variable, binomial probability distribution, geometrical probability.      General Terminology     Random Experiment: An experiment whose outcome is known. e.g., tossing a coin, throwing a dice, drawing a card, etc.     Sample Space: Set of all possible outcomes. e.g., sample space of throwing a dice, . Here, 1, 2, 3,... etc. are sample points (or, sample outcomes); sample space of tossing a coin, .     Event: Subset of sample space. Getting an odd number in a dice. e.g.       Null Event: It has no outcome, or no element in it. For example suppose a sample space Now, an event, A = number greater than 6.  It is also called impossible or void event.     Simple Event: It is also called singleton event. It contains only one element or one outcome.  an event, B = Even prime number.       Mixed or Compound Events: Events that have more than one outcome but less than all.  C = prime numbers.      Sure Event: It is equal to sample space. e.g.,  D = all number less than 7.       Equally likely events: Having equal chances of occurrence.     Mutually exclusive or disjoint or incompatible events: Events whose simultaneous occurrence is impossible. (getting a head and a tail at the same time is not possible in tossing a coin.) In mutually exclusive events there are nothing in common.  Let = prime numbers, and = composite numbers.      Exhaustive Event: Two or more events that build complete set or sample space. If = even numbers, and = odd numbers, then           Probability Formula   If a random experiment has total of mutually exclusive, mutually exhaustive, and equally likely outcomes, out of which there are favorable events , then the probability of occurrence of event is denoted by    In sample space, each sample points are equally likely events, then we can find the probability of occurrence using . However, if they are not equally likely then can not be used directly.   Note: If all outcomes of sample space are not equally likely, then here, in sample space,  are not equally likely outcomes, then cannot be applied.    A coin is tossed, if it shows head then toss it again, otherwise throw a dice. Here,      = getting two heads.     = getting an odd number.     = getting tail in outcome.       The sample space,   has total outcomes = 8, but each outcome has different probability, i.e., they are not equally likely.                     The probability of event is given by    The probability of for getting and for getting .     The probability of for getting in a coin and for getting or , etc in a dice.      The probability of for getting and for getting .        Important Note:    Sum of probabilities of each sample point = 1.  or, probability of sample space = 1.  If sample space,     If then is impossible event.  If then is sure or certain event.  Hence,     Probability of non-occurrence of event,        Useful Set-Formulae for Probability       "
